alternatives.transcript: just finished meeting with leslie palmer she's a sixty two year old female who presented with chest pain shortness of breath and fatigue she mentioned this started three weeks ago when she had a cold she said the chest pain was on her left side just above her left breast and rated it as dull constant and achy and a two out of ten she said it did not radiate anywhere and for the shortness of breath she said it was relieved by sitting up and bothered her more while lying down she was awake alert oriented but i did note she was fatigued her vitals were a heart rate of one hundred and ten so slightly elevated a respiratory rate of twenty oxygen stats at ninety one percent which i told her was low and her respiratory rate slightly high probably as a compensation for that her temperature was normal at ninety eight point six and her blood pressure was slightly elevated at one hundred and thirty over ninety however she does have a history of hypertension so that may be normal for her for her general review of systems she had fatigue and a weight gain of ten of eight pounds everything else was negative her skin heat and neuro review of systems were all negative for her cardio she had chest pain and palpitations but no near syncope and for her pulmonary review of system she had wheezing dyspnea and orthnea and for her msk she had lower extremity edema that she mentioned so as i said her past medical history is positive for hypertension for which she takes lisinopril ten milligrams orally every day she has no surgical history or hospitalizations or no known drug allergies her mother passed away at eighty years old of breast cancer her father is currently eighty nine who is living in a care facility with alzheimer's for her personal social history she eats a well balanced diet she says she was exercising regularly up until the chest pain and shortness of breath and so she is not currently exercising she denies any drugs tobacco or alcohol use and drinks one cup of coffee per day her occupation is an elementary school teacher and she lives with her husband who she's married to i asked her about the shortness of breath for which she said it occurs at rest so that would be a grade four nyh scale on physical exam i noted that she was positive for jugular venous distension she did not have any bruise her heart rate was regular with no murmurs regurgitation or gallops her pmi was displaced laterally she did not have any chest wall tenderness but on auscultation she did have five basilar rails and wheezing on her lower extremity exam i noticed plus one pitting edema in the calves her calves were not tender and her pulses were full and normal going over her lab work with her i noted her troponins were high as well as her bnp was elevated at four thousand her chest x-ray showed cardiomegaly and pulmonary edema and her echo showed a dilated cardiomyopathy with reduced ejection fraction the ekg showed sinus tach which was consistent with the monitor we had on her and a right bundle branch block so based on the physical exam history and lab work i diagnosed myocarditis dilated cardiomyopathy so we are admitting her to the hospital with telemetry serious condition so we are gonna check vitals every two hours activity i left as tolerated for nursing interventions strict input output maintaining daily weight and dvt prophylaxis and putting a nasal cannula on to maintain her oxygen status above ninety six for iv fluids we're gonna add furosemide at forty milligrams iv to help with the pulmonary edema and so i left iv fluid status as keep veins open i prescribed six hundred twenty five milligrams of oral acetaminophen for the pain and told her she could continue her ten milligrams of lisinopril daily for her cardiovascular system ten milligrams of lisinopril daily for her cardiovascular system no other respiratory therapy besides the nasal cannula for lab orders i ordered a cmp and serial troponins and a follow-up two d echo as well and then consulted radiology cardiology and infectious disease so that we could get an aicd placed a crtd and do a biopsy as well as getting her glucocorticoids and a media enhanced mri so she will be admitted into the hospital and we should check-in with her frequently but for now that is all thank you very much
